<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - DRIVETRAIN FAILURE ANALYSIS - TRANSMISSION COMPONENTS -
        BEARINGS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="7">
        <title>BEARINGS</title>
        <para>Under normal conditions the service life of a transmission is determined by the life of the bearings.
            Premature bearing failure falls into the following categories:
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Torsional vibration can cause the bearing cage to fail, allowing the balls to move and not
                carry the load evenly. The inner race will have a sharp edge along the edge (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300205">Figure 5</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300205" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300205" filename="../figg13/G1300205.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Sharp Edge Along Inner Race</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Contaminated lubricant will cause inner race spalling (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300206">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300206" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300206" filename="../figg13/G1300206.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Inner Race Spalling</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <para>Fatigue is characterized by flaking or spalling of the bearing raceway (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1300207">Figure 7</hotlnk>). Spalling is a granular weakening of the bearing steel which
            causes it to flake away from the raceway. The rough surface of spalled bearings will produce noise and
            vibration.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1300207" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1300207" filename="../figg13/G1300207.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 7. Flaking or Spalling of Bearing Raceway</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lack of lubricant is characterized by discoloration of the bearing parts and spalling of the
                raceway (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300208">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300208" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300208" filename="../figg13/G1300208.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Spalling of Raceway</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Improper assembly can cause brinelling (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300209">Figure 9</hotlnk>). Driving or pressing on one race while supporting the other
                is the primary cause.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300209" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300209" filename="../figg13/G1300209.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Brinelling</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Overloading will appear as shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300207">Figure 7</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Misalignment is indicated by offset spalling (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300210">Figure 10</hotlnk>) or an angular ball path (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300211">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300210" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300210" filename="../figg13/G1300210.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. Offset Spalling</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f1300211" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300211" filename="../figg13/G1300211.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. Angular Ball Path</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
